article.description: Marie Ferdinand scored 26 points and 7-foot-2 Margo Dydek added 12 points, 15 rebounds and seven blocked shots as the Starzz finally pulled away late to beat the Shock 86-75 Tuesday night.
article.headline: Shock make Starzz work hard, then falter late
article.linkText: Starzz forced to work harder than expected to beat Shock
article.story:
AUBURN HILLS, Mich. (AP) -- The Utah Starzz saw the Detroit Shock's record and expected an easy game. It didn't turn out that way. Marie Ferdinand scored 26 points and 7-foot-2 Margo Dydek added 12 points, 15 rebounds and seven blocked shots as the Starzz finally pulled away late to beat the Shock 86-75 Tuesday night. "It was hard to get up for this game, but we had to play hard in the second half,'' Ferdinand said. "Detroit's a lot better than their record -- that is definitely a team of the future.'' Detroit had its four-game home-winning streak snapped. Utah (16-7) has beaten the Shock (4-18) three straight times after losing five of the first six meetings. "We left everything out there,'' Starzz coach Candi Harvey said. "Marie is a great player for us, and when Margo starts blocking shots like that, we are tough to beat.'' Adrienne Goodson added 22 points for Utah, while Swin Cash led the Shock with 21. Deanna Nolan added 13. "We know we could have beaten this team tonight, but we missed too many lay-ups and free throws,'' Nolan said. "With that big girl in the middle, you really have to readjust your shots.'' Detroit led 35-32 at the half thanks to eight points each from Barbara Farris and Cash. Farris outscored Dydek by four points in the half despite an 11-inch disadvantage in height. Utah regained the lead early in the second half, and the teams swapped the advantage for most of the period. Detroit led 61-59 with 6:52 left, but Utah scored the next seven points, including four from Johnson. Dydek added two blocks and a tip-in of a missed free throw. "Their big lady in there really hurt us,'' Shock coach Bill Laimbeer said. "We like to attack the basket, and with the big tree in there, it caused us some problems.'' The Shock didn't get another field goal until Nolan's 3-pointer that cut Utah's lead to 78-69 with 54 seconds left. "That was just desperation,'' Laimbeer said. "We played fairly decent in the first half, but we didn't get it done down the stretch.''

Game notes
Utah played without starting forward Natalie Williams, who missed the game to attend her grandmother's funeral. Semeka Randall, acquired in a trade Monday with Seattle, will not join the team until their next game. ... Pistons forward Corliss Williamson, the NBA's Sixth Man of the Year, attended the game. ... Dydek holds the league record with 10 blocks in a game. ... The game was delayed briefly in the second half when a few victory streamers fell prematurely from the rafters.
